		<title>Dogs and Concepts &#8211; Learning Beyond Behaviours</title>
		<link>http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/archives/dogs-and-concepts-learning-beyond-behaviours</link>
		<comments>http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/archives/dogs-and-concepts-learning-beyond-behaviours#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 01 May 2012 02:59:46 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Eric Brad</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Current Buzz]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Featured]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Podcast]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[featured]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/?p=1044</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[“Sit.” “Down.” “Fetch.”  These are things that most people associate with dog training.  But is there more we can teach our dogs beyond simple behaviours?  You might be surprised that you already do!  And there might be more you can teach them.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Audio edition of the article <a href="http://lifeasahuman.com/2012/pets/dogs-and-concepts-learning-beyond-behaviours/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"><strong>Dogs and Concepts – Learning Beyond Behaviours</strong></a> from the Life As A Human online magazine website. You can visit <a href="http://caninenation.lifeasahuman.com/" target="_blank">Life as a Human</a> to find this and other articles.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/concepts.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-1046" title="concepts" src="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/concepts.jpg" alt="" width="286" height="300" /></a>“Sit.” “Down.” “Fetch.”  These are things that most people associate with dog training.  But is there more we can teach our dogs beyond simple behaviours?  You might be surprised that you already do!  And there might be more you can teach them.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s not hard to teach our dogs to do &#8220;tricks.&#8221;  They are, after all, just behaviours.  But how do you teach a dog to think about things like &#8220;bigger and smaller&#8221; or &#8220;closer or farther away&#8221;?  Our dogs have the capacity to learn such things and they do it every day.  What if we could engage that conceptual learning?  What might be possible if we trained beyond just behaviours?</p>
<p>Thanks for listening to Canine Nation podcasts. I hope you can spread the word and let your dog-friends know about what you&#8217;re hearing here. As always, your comments and suggestions are welcome!</p>
 <img src="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/plugins/wordpress-feed-statistics/feed-statistics.php?view=1&post_id=1044" width="1" height="1" style="display: none;" />]]></content:encoded>
