		<title>The Crossover Files – Positively Frustrating Dog Training</title>
		<link>http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/archives/the-crossover-files-positively-frustrating-dog-training</link>
		<comments>http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/archives/the-crossover-files-positively-frustrating-dog-training#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 30 Apr 2012 01:00:18 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Eric Brad</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Current Buzz]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Podcast]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[featured]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/?p=1036</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Crossing over to positive training can be frustrating.  Abandoning old techniques for new is uncomfortable.  Especially when you aren’t good at the new stuff.  Dog trainer Eric Brad has found that sticking with positive training is well worth the effort for the rewards that come later.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Audio edition of the article <a href="http://lifeasahuman.com/2012/pets/the-crossover-files-positively-frustrating-dog-training/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"><strong>The Crossover Files – Positively Frustrating Dog Training</strong></a> from the Life As A Human online magazine website. You can visit <a href="http://caninenation.lifeasahuman.com/" target="_blank">Life as a Human</a> to find this and other articles.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/archives/the-crossover-files-positively-frustrating-dog-training/positively" rel="attachment wp-att-1037"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-1037" title="positively" src="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/positively.jpg" alt="" width="298" height="300" /></a>Crossing over to positive training can be frustrating.  Abandoning old techniques for new is uncomfortable.  Especially when you aren’t good at the new stuff.  Dog trainer Eric Brad has found that sticking with positive training is well worth the effort for the rewards that come later.</p>
<p>Back when I was crossing over to positive training, it seemed like every time I turned around another technique I used to use was now a bad idea.  I had to keep running back to books or asking questions of positive trainers online to find appropriate alternatives.  But the answers were there and my new habits developed quickly.  But not as quickly as my relationship with my dogs improved!  It was well worth the extra work.</p>
<p>Thanks for listening to Canine Nation podcasts. I hope you can spread the word and let your dog-friends know about what you&#8217;re hearing here. As always, your comments and suggestions are welcome!</p>
 <img src="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/plugins/wordpress-feed-statistics/feed-statistics.php?view=1&post_id=1036" width="1" height="1" style="display: none;" />]]></content:encoded>
