		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/?p=1028</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Do you ask your dog to do things for you or do you tell them to do them?  How we think about working with our dogs matters.  It affects our expectations and can lead to cooperation or conflict.  It seems to be an AND/OR proposition.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Audio edition of the article <a href="http://lifeasahuman.com/2012/pets/dog-training-andor-what-comes-next/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"><strong>Dog Training And/Or What Comes Next</strong></a> from the Life As A Human online magazine website. You can visit <a href="http://caninenation.lifeasahuman.com/" target="_blank">Life as a Human</a> to find this and other articles.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/andornext.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-1029" title="andornext" src="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/andornext.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="284" /></a>Do you ask your dog to do things for you or do you tell them to do them?  How we think about working with our dogs matters.  It affects our expectations and can lead to cooperation or conflict.  It seems to be an AND/OR proposition.</p>
<p>Is working with your dog a cooperative offer or is it a &#8220;do it or else&#8221; proposition for your dog?  Your dogs willingness to work with you might be at stake.  It&#8217;s not just about getting results.  HOW you get those results can make all the difference.</p>
<p>Thanks for listening to Canine Nation podcasts. I hope you can spread the word and let your dog-friends know about what you&#8217;re hearing here. As always, your comments and suggestions are welcome!</p>
