		<title>My &#8220;Dominant&#8221; Dog and How I Cope</title>
		<link>http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/archives/my-dominant-dog-and-how-i-cope</link>
		<comments>http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/archives/my-dominant-dog-and-how-i-cope#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 01 Mar 2012 01:52:58 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Eric Brad</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Current Buzz]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Podcast]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[featured]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/?p=886</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Is your dog “dominant” or willing to submit?  Could you be living with a dog determined to take over and control your household?  Dog Trainer Eric Brad looks as his own dog to see if the “warning signs” described by so many web sites could mean his dog is a tyrant in the making!]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Audio edition of the article <a href="http://lifeasahuman.com/2012/pets/my-dominant-dog-and-how-i-cope/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"><strong>My “Dominant” Dog and How I Cope</strong></a> from the Life As A Human online magazine website. You can visit <a href="http://caninenation.lifeasahuman.com/" target="_blank">Life as a Human</a> to find this and other articles.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/bugsy-300x259.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-888" title="bugsy-300x259" src="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/bugsy-300x259.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="259" /></a>Is your dog “dominant” or willing to submit?  Could you be living with a dog determined to take over and control your household?  Dog Trainer Eric Brad looks as his own dog to see if the “warning signs” described by so many web sites could mean his dog is a tyrant in the making!</p>
<p>There are lots of websites out there that will tell you just how badly behaved your dog might be.  And most of them will happily tell you how to &#8220;correct&#8221; these signs of &#8220;aggression&#8221; and &#8220;dominance&#8221; to keep your dog from thinking he&#8217;s the &#8220;alpha&#8221; in your pack.  But you may have to agree to a price first.</p>
<p>The truth is, dogs are not pack animals.  They are domesticated companion animals bred by humans.  And those &#8220;warning signs&#8221; some web sites caution you about may just be natural behaviours or indicators of something totally different.</p>
