		<title>Some Dogs Won’t Work For Food</title>
		<link>http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/archives/some-dogs-wont-work-for-food</link>
		<comments>http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/archives/some-dogs-wont-work-for-food#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 10 Jan 2012 19:15:49 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Eric Brad</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Current Buzz]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Podcast]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/?p=828</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Food is something every dog has every day.  Unless they are ill, there should be no reason for our dogs to turn down any snacks we offer them.  But many dog owners claim their dogs won’t work for them for food treats as a reward.  How can this be?  Dogs are scavengers by nature.  Could it be something we humans are doing that puts them off sometimes?]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Audio edition of the article <a href="http://lifeasahuman.com/2011/pets/some-dogs-wont-work-for-food/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"><strong>Some Dogs Won’t Work For Food</strong></a> from the Life As A Human online magazine website. You can visit <a href="http://caninenation.lifeasahuman.com/" target="_blank">Life as a Human</a> to find this and other articles.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/work4food.jpg"><img class="alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-829" title="work4food" src="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/work4food-290x290.jpg" alt="" width="290" height="290" /></a>Food is something every dog has every day.  Unless they are ill, there should be no reason for our dogs to turn down any snacks we offer them.  But many dog owners claim their dogs won’t work for them for food treats as a reward.  How can this be?  Dogs are scavengers by nature.  Could it be something we humans are doing that puts them off sometimes?</p>
<p>There can be other reasons dogs won&#8217;t take food such as anxiety, distraction, or arousal.  It&#8217;s best to make sure that a dog is within their tolerance for these things <em>before</em> attempting to train them or offer them food.  Failing to do so could create more problems than it solves.</p>
<p>Thanks for listening to Canine Nation podcasts. I hope you can spread the word and let your dog-friends know about what you&#8217;re hearing here. As always, your comments and suggestions are welcome!</p>
