		<item>
		<title>A Closer Look At Self Rewarding Behaviour</title>
		<link>http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/archives/a-closer-look-at-self-rewarding-behaviour</link>
		<comments>http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/archives/a-closer-look-at-self-rewarding-behaviour#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 21 Dec 2011 00:59:26 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Eric Brad</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Current Buzz]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.caninenation.ca/?p=786</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Sometimes our dogs don’t want to do what we ask of them.  Sometimes the rewards we offer them are not enough and they turn to “self-rewarding” behaviours.  But are those behaviours really self-rewarding?  It’s what our dog chooses to do so it must be.  But what else is “self-rewarding” behaviour?  The answer might surprise you.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Audio edition of the article <a href="http://lifeasahuman.com/2011/pets/a-closer-look-at-self-rewarding-behaviour/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"><strong>A Closer Look At Self Rewarding Behaviour</strong></a> from the Life As A Human online magazine website. You can visit <a href="http://lifeasahuman.com/category/pets/canine-nation/" target="_blank">Life a a Human</a> to find this and other articles.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.caninenation.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/self-rewarding.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-745" title="Selfrewarding" src="http://www.caninenation.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/self-rewarding.jpg" alt="" width="283" height="300" /></a>Sometimes our dogs don’t want to do what we ask of them.  Sometimes the rewards we offer them are not enough and they turn to “self-rewarding” behaviours.  But are those behaviours really self-rewarding?  It’s what our dog chooses to do so it must be.  But what else is “self-rewarding” behaviour?  The answer might surprise you.</p>
<p>Reinforcement and Rewards are not necessarily the same thing.  As trainers, we owe it to our dogs to know when we&#8217;re <em>trying</em> to train something and when we&#8217;re just rewarding them for being our dogs.  Both are important and both are in our control as trainers.</p>
<p>Thanks for listening to Canine Nation podcasts. I hope you can spread the word and let your dog-friends know about what you&#8217;re hearing here. As always, your comments and suggestions are welcome!</p>
 <img src="http://www.frivoli.com/caninenation/wp-content/plugins/wordpress-feed-statistics/feed-statistics.php?view=1&post_id=786" width="1" height="1" style="display: none;" />]]></content:encoded>
