			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img style="float: right; margin-left: 15px; margin-right: 15px;" src="http://lifeasahuman.com/files/2011/06/Rizzo-standing-300x199.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="199" />Audio edition of the article <a href="http://lifeasahuman.com/2011/pets/how-do-we-talk-about-dog-training/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"><strong>How Do We Talk About Dog Training?</strong></a> from the Life As A Human online magazine website. You can visit <a href="http://lifeasahuman.com/category/pets/canine-nation/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Canine Nation</a> to find this and other articles.</p>
<p><span style="font-size: small;">The terms we use to describe when we talk about dogs and dog behaviour matters. Sometimes generalizing too much can do more harm than good. While clever terms can get you to agreement on some level, they may also keep us from understanding what each other is REALLY talking about.</span></p>
<p>This week I&#8217;m recommending a great DVD set. &#8220;Fundamentals of Animal Training&#8221; by Bob Bailey is a tremendous value. Bob has more than 40 experience in training animals from dolphins and whales to lizards, bears, and dogs! His presentation is fun, informative, he brings even complex topic into an easy to understand focus. You can find it at <a href="http://www.dogwise.com/itemdetails.cfm?ID=DTB893" target="_blank">the Dogwise online store.</a> Check them out out!</p>
